# Festag — no transition flashes between chromes

Never leave a visible flash of the **previous** screen’s design when navigating between Festag chromes (auth landings, Docs, legal, portal).

## Chromes

| Chrome | Canvas (light) | Typical routes |
|---|---|---|
| Auth landing | `#f7f8f8` / dark `#0f0f11` | `/login`, `/register`, `/onboarding`, `/dev/login` |
| Docs | `#FCFCFD` / dark `#000` | `/docs`, `/docs/*` |
| Legal | `#ffffff` (always light) | `/agb`, `/datenschutz`, … |
| Portal | `#F5F5F7` / dark `#000` | dashboard, projects, … |

## Rules

1. **Before** client navigation that leaves a chrome, call `prepareAuthRouteTransition(href)` / `applyAppearanceForPath(path)` so the **destination** canvas paints first.
2. Auth → Docs from the Docs popup: use `navigateLeavingAuthChrome(href)` (hard assign after canvas prep) — soft-nav overlap was flashing portal/auth under Docs.
3. Do **not** put `/docs` in `isPortalShellRoute` — Docs is its own shell, not `PortalAppShell`.
4. FOUC script in `app/layout.tsx` must know auth + docs + legal landings (`data-auth-landing` / `data-docs-landing`).
5. Prefer opaque exit (`.exiting`) over fading auth to `opacity:0` (that flashed white under dark auth).

## Do not

- Plain `<a href="/docs/…">` from auth without transition prep
- Soft-nav that leaves the old React tree visible on a portal-colored body
- Assume ThemeProvider `useLayoutEffect` alone is enough — prep **before** `router.push` / assign
